# Revenue by Segment

Apple's revenue diversification continues to evolve, with the iPhone remaining the primary growth engine while Services cements its position as a critical second pillar.

```mdcc_chart caption="Revenue Distribution by Product Segment (Q1 2026 vs Q1 2025)" label="fig:segment-revenue"
# Data preparation
segments = ["iPhone", "Services", "Mac", "iPad", "Wearables"]
rev_2026 = [85.3, 30.0, 8.4, 8.6, 11.5]
rev_2025 = [69.35, 26.32, 9.03, 8.11, 11.73]

df = pd.DataFrame({
    "Segment": segments * 2,
    "Revenue": rev_2026 + rev_2025,
    "Year": ["2026"] * 5 + ["2025"] * 5
})

# Create Chart
chart = alt.Chart(df).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("Year:N", title=None),
    y=alt.Y("Revenue:Q", title="Revenue ($ Billions)"),
    color=alt.Color("Year:N", scale=alt.Scale(range=["#0071E3", "#86868B"])),
    column=alt.Column("Segment:N", title="Segment", header=alt.Header(labelOrient="bottom", titleOrient="bottom"))
).properties(
    width=100,
    height=300
).configure_view(
    stroke=None
)

chart
```

As visualized in @fig:segment-revenue, the **iPhone segment** saw a massive $16 billion increase in quarterly revenue, reflecting a dominant upgrade cycle. Conversely, the Mac and Wearables segments faced slight headwinds due to difficult year-over-year comparisons and specific product constraints.

